rmalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\\nRead and follow the instructions in .claude/agents/reviewer.md\\n\\nRequirements folder: \\n\\nYour task:\\n1. Read .claude/agents/reviewer.md for your role and process\\n2. Read /README.md for requirements context\\n3. Read any existing review-NN.md files to understand previous feedback\\n4. Review branch changes: git diff main...HEAD -- . ':!.entire'\\n5. Systematically check against the review checklist\\n6. Write review to /review-NN.md (increment NN from last review)\\n7. Verdict: APPROVE or REQUEST CHANGES\\n\",\"agentId\":\"a4e598f\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01NMSPbwfxFWrXqycKMgN6ZG\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_012Ca65cAWrr997pfNhjMg7p\",\"uuid\":\"2fc03fbd-1b16-4dbd-8cae-c318f9740ca5\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T13:14:23.086Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"2fc03fbd-1b16-4dbd-8cae-c318f9740ca5\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"5fa62c96-990b-404b-ba97-2d130d82ab6e\",\"version\":\"2.1.17\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-refactor\",\"slug\":\"eager-tickling-nova\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_013sc1YyKQ4ZRFXbFKyLfEDR\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→---\\n     2→name: reviewer\\n     3→description: Code review agent - critically reviews changes for quality, security, and correctness\\n     4→model: opus\\n     5→color: green\\n     6→---\\n     7→\\n     8→# Senior Code Reviewer Agent\\n     9→\\n    10→You are a **Senior Code Reviewer** with decades of experience across multiple languages and domains. Your role is to provide thorough, constructive, and actionable feedback.\\n    11→\\n    12→## Scoping the Review\\n    13→\\n    14→**Always scope your review to the current branch:**\\n    15→\\n    16→1. Find the base branch: `git log --oneline main..HEAD` or `git merge-base main HEAD`\\n    17→2. Review branch changes: `git diff main...HEAD -- . ':!.entire'`\\n    18→3. Exclude from diff (not code):\\n    19→   - `.entire/` - conversation history\\n    20→   - `docs/requirements/*/task-*.md` - task tracking files\\n    21→\\n    22→**Why branch-scoped?** The `entire` tool auto-commits after each interaction, so `git diff` alone will show noise. Comparing against the base branch shows the actual feature work.\\n    23→\\n    24→## Review Philosophy\\n    25→\\n    26→- **Be Critical, Be Kind** - Find issues, but explain them constructively\\n    27→- **Assume Good Intent** - The developer tried their best; help them improve\\n    28→- **Focus on What Matters** - Prioritize issues by impact\\n    29→- **Teach, Don't Dictate** - Explain the \\\"why\\\" behind feedback\\n    30→\\n    31→## Review Checklist\\n    32→\\n    33→### 1. Correctness\\n    34→- Does the code do what the requirements specify?\\n    35→- Are all acceptance criteria met?\\n    36→- Are there logic errors or off-by-one bugs?\\n    37→\\n    38→### 2. Edge Cases\\n    39→- What happens with null/undefined/empty inputs?\\n    40→- Boundary conditions (0, 1, max values)?\\n    41→- Concurrent access scenarios?\\n    42→- Network failures, timeouts?\\n    43→\\n    44→### 3. Security\\n    45→- Input validation (SQL injection, XSS, command injection)?\\n    46→- Authentication/authorization properly enforced?\\n    47→- Sensitive data exposure (logs, errors, responses)?\\n    48→- Dependency vulnerabilities?\\n    49→\\n    50→### 4. Scalability\\n    51→- O(n) complexity issues that could blow up?\\n    52→- N+1 query problems?\\n    53→- Memory leaks or unbounded growth?\\n    54→- Appropriate caching considerations?\\n    55→\\n    56→### 5. Usability\\n    57→- Clear error messages for users?\\n    58→- Appropriate logging for operators?\\n    59→- API design intuitive and consistent?\\n    60→\\n    61→### 6. Code Quality\\n    62→- Readable and self-documenting?\\n    63→- Appropriate abstraction level (not over/under-engineered)?\\n    64→- Follows project conventions and patterns?\\n    65→- No code duplication (DRY)?\\n    66→\\n    67→### 7. Test Coverage\\n    68→- Are the tests actually testing the right things?\\n    69→- Edge cases covered in tests?\\n    70→- Tests are readable and maintainable?\\n    71→- No testing implementation details (brittle tests)?\\n    72→\\n    73→### 8. End-to-End Verification\\n    74→**CRITICAL: Don't just verify code exists - verify it actually works.**\\n    75→\\n    76→For each acceptance criterion in the requirements:\\n    77→- Trace the full code path from entry point to expected outcome\\n    78→- Confirm there's an integration test that exercises the complete behavior\\n    79→- If the criterion says \\\"X produces Y\\\", verify that running X actually produces Y\\n    80→\\n    81→Surface-level checks (code present, functions defined) are insufficient. The feature must be wired up end-to-end. If integration test coverage is missing, flag as **Critical**.\\n    82→\\n    83→### 9. Documentation\\n    84→- Public APIs documented?\\n    85→- Complex logic explained where necessary?\\n    86→- README/docs updated if needed?\\n    87→\\n    88→## Feedback Format\\n    89→\\n    90→Provide feedback in this structure:\\n    91→\\n    92→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    93→Issues that must be addressed before merge:\\n    94→- **[File:Line]** Issue description. Suggested fix.\\n    95→\\n    96→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    97→Issues that should be addressed:\\n    98→- **[File:Line]** Issue description. Suggested fix.\\n    99→\\n   100→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n   101→Optional improvements:\\n   102→- **[File:Line]** Suggestion. Rationale.\\n   103→\\n   104→### Praise\\n   105→What was done well (reinforces good patterns):\\n   106→- Good use of X pattern in Y\\n   107→\\n   108→### Summary\\n   109→- Overall assessment: APPROVE / REQUEST CHANGES / NEEDS DISCUSSION\\n   110→- Key concerns (if any)\\n   111→- Estimated effort to address feedback\\n   112→\\n   113→## Review History\\n   114→\\n   115→**Before reviewing, check for previous reviews:**\\n   116→\\n   117→1. List existing reviews: `ls [requirements-folder]/review-*.md`\\n   118→2. Read previous reviews to understand:\\n   119→   - What issues were raised before\\n   120→   - Whether those issues have been addressed\\n   121→   - Patterns of feedback (recurring issues?)\\n   122→3. In your new review, explicitly note:\\n   123→   - Which previous issues are now fixed\\n   124→   - Which previous issues are still outstanding\\n   125→\\n   126→## Output\\n   127→\\n   128→Write your review to a file in the requirements folder:\\n   129→\\n   130→1. Find the next review number:\\n   131→   ```bash\\n   132→   ls [requirements-folder]/review-*.md 2>/dev/null | wc -l\\n   133→   # If 0 → review-01.md, if 1 → review-02.md, etc.\\n   134→   ```\\n   135→2. Write to: `[requirements-folder]/review-NN.md`\\n   136→3. Example: `docs/requirements/jaja-bot/review-01.md`\\n   137→\\n   138→**Review file format:**\\n   139→```markdown\\n   140→# Review NN\\n   141→\\n   142→> Status: pending-dev | in-progress | addressed\\n   143→> Date: [date]\\n   144→> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n   145→> Verdict: APPROVE | REQUEST CHANGES\\n   146→\\n   147→## Previous Review Status\\n   148→- [x] Issue from review-01: [description] - FIXED\\n   149→- [ ] Issue from review-01: [description] - STILL OUTSTANDING\\n   150→\\n   151→## New Findings\\n   152→[Use the feedback format from above]\\n   153→\\n   154→## Summary\\n   155→[Overall assessment]\\n   156→```\\n   157→\\n   158→**Review status workflow:**\\n   159→- `pending-dev` - Review written, waiting for developer to address\\n   160→- `in-progress` - Developer is actively working on feedback\\n   161→- `addressed` - Developer has addressed all feedback (ready for next review)\\n   162→\\n   163→This allows:\\n   164→- Developer agent to read feedback directly\\n   165→- History of review iterations in git\\n   166→- Clear handoff between agents\\n   167→- Tracking of issue resolution across iterations\\n   168→\\n\\n<system-reminder>\\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\\n</system-reminder>\\n\"}]},\"uuid\":\"8c8c6e98-5f7e-438a-9594-79a82cc6a1e1\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T13:14:23.126Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\\nRead and follow the instructions in .claude/agents/reviewer.md\\n\\nRequirements folder: \\n\\nYour task:\\n1. Read .claude/agents/reviewer.md for your role and process\\n2. Read /README.md for requirements context\\n3. Read any existing review-NN.md files to understand previous feedback\\n4. Review branch changes: git diff main...HEAD -- . ':!.entire'\\n5. Systematically check against the review checklist\\n6. Write review to /review-NN.md (increment NN from last review)\\n7. Verdict: APPROVE or REQUEST CHANGES\\n\",\"agentId\":\"a4e598f\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01NMSPbwfxFWrXqycKMgN6ZG\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_012Ca65cAWrr997pfNhjMg7p\",\"uuid\":\"6041d414-b7d7-4959-8ca2-3ba363aefc96\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T13:14:23.148Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"6041d414-b7d7-4959-8ca2-3ba363aefc96\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"5fa62c96-990b-404b-ba97-2d130d82ab6e\",\"version\":\"2.1.17\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-refactor\",\"slug\":\"eager-tickling-nova\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01AJVWxCMtr47A6UxR7fagB1\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Entire CLI\\n     2→\\n     3→Entire hooks into your git workflow to capture AI agent sessions on every push. Sessions are indexed alongside commits, creating a searchable record of how code was written in your repo.\\n     4→\\n     5→With Entire, you can:\\n     6→\\n     7→* **Understand why code changed** — see the full prompt/response transcript and files touched\\n     8→* **Recover instantly** — rewind to a known-good checkpoint when an agent goes sideways and resume seamlessly\\n     9→* **Keep Git history clean** — preserve agent context on a separate branch\\n    10→* **Onboard faster** — show the path from prompt → change → commit\\n    11→* **Maintain traceability** — support audit and compliance requirements when needed\\n    12→\\n    13→## Table of Contents\\n    14→\\n    15→- [Quick Start](#quick-start)\\n    16→- [Typical Workflow](#typical-workflow)\\n    17→- [Key Concepts](#key-concepts)\\n    18→  - [How It Works](#how-it-works)\\n    19→  - [Strategies](#strategies)\\n    20→- [Commands Reference](#commands-reference)\\n    21→- [Configuration](#configuration)\\n    22→- [Security & Privacy](#security--privacy)\\n    23→- [Troubleshooting](#troubleshooting)\\n    24→- [Development](#development)\\n    25→- [Getting Help](#getting-help)\\n    26→- [License](#license)\\n    27→\\n    28→## Requirements\\n    29→\\n    30→- Git\\n    31→- macOS or Linux (Windows via WSL)\\n    32→- [Claude Code](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code) or [Gemini CLI](https://github.com/google-gemini/gemini-cli) installed and authenticated\\n    33→\\n    34→## Quick Start\\n    35→\\n    36→```bash\\n    37→# Install via Homebrew\\n    38→brew tap entireio/tap\\n    39→brew install entireio/tap/entire\\n    40→\\n    41→# Or install via Go\\n    42→go install github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire@latest\\n    43→\\n    44→# Enable in your project\\n    45→cd your-project && entire enable\\n    46→\\n    47→# Check status\\n    48→entire status\\n    49→```\\n    50→\\n    51→## Typical Workflow\\n    52→\\n    53→### 1. Enable Entire in Your Repository\\n    54→\\n    55→```\\n    56→entire enable\\n    57→```\\n    58→\\n    59→This installs agent and git hooks to work with your AI agent (Claude Code or Gemini CLI). The hooks capture session data at specific points in your workflow. Your code commits stay clean—all session metadata is stored on a separate `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch.\\n    60→\\n    61→**When checkpoints are created** depends on your chosen strategy (default is `manual-commit`):\\n    62→- **Manual-commit**: Checkpoints are created when you or the agent make a git commit\\n    63→- **Auto-commit**: Checkpoints are created after each agent response\\n    64→\\n    65→### 2. Work with Your AI Agent\\n    66→\\n    67→Just use Claude Code or Gemini CLI normally. Entire runs in the background, tracking your session:\\n    68→\\n    69→```\\n    70→entire status  # Check current session status anytime\\n    71→```\\n    72→\\n    73→### 3. Rewind to a Previous Checkpoint\\n    74→\\n    75→If you want to undo some changes and go back to an earlier checkpoint:\\n    76→\\n    77→```\\n    78→entire rewind\\n    79→```\\n    80→\\n    81→This shows all available checkpoints in the current session. Select one to restore your code to that exact state.\\n    82→\\n    83→### 4. Resume a Previous Session\\n    84→\\n    85→To restore the latest checkpointed session metadata for a branch:\\n    86→\\n    87→```\\n    88→entire resume <branch>\\n    89→```\\n    90→\\n    91→Entire checks out the branch, restores the latest checkpointed session metadata (one or more sessions), and prints command(s) to continue.\\n    92→\\n    93→### 5. Disable Entire (Optional)\\n    94→\\n    95→```\\n    96→entire disable\\n    97→```\\n    98→\\n    99→Removes the git hooks. Your code and commit history remain untouched.\\n   100→\\n   101→## Key Concepts\\n   102→\\n   103→### Sessions\\n   104→\\n   105→A **session** represents a complete interaction with your AI agent, from start to finish. Each session captures all prompts, responses, files modified, and timestamps.\\n   106→\\n   107→**Session ID format:** `YYYY-MM-DD-<UUID>` (e.g., `2026-01-08-abc123de-f456-7890-abcd-ef1234567890`)\\n   108→\\n   109→Sessions are stored separately from your code commits on the `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch.\\n   110→\\n   111→### Checkpoints\\n   112→\\n   113→A **checkpoint** is a snapshot within a session that you can rewind to—a \\\"save point\\\" in your work.\\n   114→\\n   115→**When checkpoints are created:**\\n   116→\\n   117→- **Manual-commit strategy**: When you or the agent make a git commit\\n   118→- **Auto-commit strategy**: After each agent response\\n   119→\\n   120→**Checkpoint IDs** are 12-character hex strings (e.g., `a3b2c4d5e6f7`).\\n   121→\\n   122→### How It Works\\n   123→\\n   124→```\\n   125→Your Branch                    entire/checkpoints/v1\\n   126→     │                                  │\\n   127→     ▼                                  │\\n   128→[Base Commit]                           │\\n   129→     │                                  │\\n   130→     │  ┌─── Agent works ───┐           │\\n   131→     │  │  Step 1           │           │\\n   132→     │  │  Step 2           │           │ \\n   133→     │  │  Step 3           │           │\\n   134→     │  └───────────────────┘           │\\n   135→     │                                  │\\n   136→     ▼                                  ▼\\n   137→[Your Commit] ─────────────────► [Session Metadata]\\n   138→     │                           (transcript, prompts,\\n   139→     │                            files touched)\\n   140→     ▼\\n   141→```\\n   142→\\n   143→Checkpoints are saved as you work. When you commit, session metadata is permanently stored on the `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch and linked to your commit.\\n   144→\\n   145→### Strategies\\n   146→\\n   147→Entire offers two strategies for capturing your work:\\n   148→\\n   149→| Aspect              | Manual-Commit                            | Auto-Commit                                        |\\n   150→| ------------------- | ---------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |\\n   151→| Code commits        | None on your branch                      | Created automatically after each agent response    |\\n   152→| Safe on main branch | Yes                                      | Use caution - creates commits on active branch     |\\n   153→| Rewind              | Always possible, non-destructive         | Full rewind on feature branches; logs-only on main |\\n   154→| Best for            | Most workflows - keeps git history clean | Teams wanting automatic code commits               |\\n   155→\\n   156→### Git Worktrees\\n   157→\\n   158→Entire works seamlessly with [git worktrees](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-worktree). Each worktree has independent session tracking, so you can run multiple AI sessions in different worktrees without conflicts.\\n   159→\\n   160→### Concurrent Sessions\\n   161→\\n   162→Multiple AI sessions can run on the same commit. If you start a second session while another has uncommitted work, Entire warns you and tracks them separately. Both sessions' checkpoints are preserved and can be rewound independently.\\n   163→\\n   164→## Commands Reference\\n   165→\\n   166→| Command          | Description                                                                   |\\n   167→| ---------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\\n   168→| `entire clean`   | Clean up orphaned Entire data                                                 |\\n   169→| `entire disable` | Remove Entire hooks from repository                                           |\\n   170→| `entire doctor`  | Fix or clean up stuck sessions                                                |\\n   171→| `entire enable`  | Enable Entire in your repository (uses `manual-commit` by default)            |\\n   172→| `entire explain` | Explain a session or commit                                                   |\\n   173→| `entire reset`   | Delete the shadow branch and session state for the current HEAD commit        |\\n   174→| `entire resume`  | Switch to a branch, restore latest checkpointed session metadata, and show command(s) to continue |\\n   175→| `entire rewind`  | Rewind to a previous checkpoint                                               |\\n   176→| `entire status`  | Show current session and strategy info                                        |\\n   177→| `entire version` | Show Entire CLI version                                                       |\\n   178→\\n   179→### `entire enable` Flags\\n   180→\\n   181→| Flag                   | Description                                                        |\\n   182→|------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n   183→| `--agent <name>`       | AI agent to setup hooks for: `claude-code` (default) or `gemini`   |\\n   184→| `--force`, `-f`        | Force reinstall hooks (removes existing Entire hooks first)        |\\n   185→| `--local`              | Write settings to `settings.local.json` instead of `settings.json` |\\n   186→| `--project`            | Write settings to `settings.json` even if it already exists        |\\n   187→| `--skip-push-sessions` | Disable automatic pushing of session logs on git push              |\\n   188→| `--strategy <name>`    | Strategy to use: `manual-commit` (default) or `auto-commit`        |\\n   189→| `--telemetry=false`    | Disable anonymous usage analytics                                  |\\n   190→\\n   191→**Examples:**\\n   192→\\n   193→```\\n   194→# Use auto-commit strategy\\n   195→entire enable --strategy auto-commit\\n   196→\\n   197→# Force reinstall hooks\\n   198→entire enable --force\\n   199→\\n   200→# Save settings locally (not committed to git)\\n   201→entire enable --local\\n   202→```\\n   203→\\n   204→## Configuration\\n   205→\\n   206→Entire uses two configuration files in the `.entire/` directory:\\n   207→\\n   208→### settings.json (Project Settings)\\n   209→\\n   210→Shared across the team, typically committed to git:\\n   211→\\n   212→```json\\n   213→{\\n   214→  \\\"strategy\\\": \\\"manual-commit\\\",\\n   215→  \\\"agent\\\": \\\"claude-code\\\",\\n   216→  \\\"enabled\\\": true\\n   217→}\\n   218→```\\n   219→\\n   220→### settings.local.json (Local Settings)\\n   221→\\n   222→Personal overrides, gitignored by default:\\n   223→\\n   224→```json\\n   225→{\\n   226→  \\\"enabled\\\": false,\\n   227→  \\\"log_level\\\": \\\"debug\\\"\\n   228→}\\n   229→```\\n   230→\\n   231→### Configuration Options\\n   232→\\n   233→| Option                               | Values                           | Description                                          |\\n   234→|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|\\n   235→| `enabled`                            | `true`, `false`                  | Enable/disable Entire                                |\\n   236→| `log_level`                          | `debug`, `info`, `warn`, `error` | Logging verbosity                                    |\\n   237→| `strategy`                           | `manual-commit`, `auto-commit`   | Session capture strategy                             |\\n   238→| `strategy_options.push_sessions`     | `true`, `false`                  | Auto-push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch on git push |\\n   239→| `strategy_options.summarize.enabled` | `true`, `false`                  | Auto-generate AI summaries at commit time            |\\n   240→| `telemetry`                          | `true`, `false`                  | Send anonymous usage statistics to Posthog           |\\n   241→\\n   242→### Auto-Summarization\\n   243→\\n   244→When enabled, Entire automatically generates AI summaries for checkpoints at commit time. Summaries capture intent, outcome, learnings, friction points, and open items from the session.\\n   245→\\n   246→```json\\n   247→{\\n   248→  \\\"strategy_options\\\": {\\n   249→    \\\"summarize\\\": {\\n   250→      \\\"enabled\\\": true\\n   251→    }\\n   252→  }\\n   253→}\\n   254→```\\n   255→\\n   256→**Requirements:**\\n   257→- Claude CLI must be installed and authenticated (`claude` command available in PATH)\\n   258→- Summary generation is non-blocking: failures are logged but don't prevent commits\\n   259→\\n   260→**Note:** Currently uses Claude CLI for summary generation. Other AI backends may be supported in future versions.\\n   261→\\n   262→### Settings Priority\\n   263→\\n   264→Local settings override project settings field-by-field. When you run `entire status`, it shows both project and local (effective) settings.\\n   265→\\n   266→### Gemini CLI (Preview)\\n   267→\\n   268→Gemini CLI support is currently in preview. Entire can work with [Gemini CLI](https://github.com/google-gemini/gemini-cli) as an alternative to Claude Code, or alongside it — you can have both agents' hooks enabled at the same time.\\n   269→\\n   270→To enable:\\n   271→\\n   272→```bash\\n   273→entire enable --agent gemini\\n   274→```\\n   275→\\n   276→All commands (`rewind`, `status`, `doctor`, etc.) work the same regardless of which agent is configured.\\n   277→\\n   278→If you run into any issues with Gemini CLI integration, please [open an issue](https://github.com/entireio/cli/issues).\\n   279→\\n   280→## Security & Privacy\\n   281→\\n   282→**Your session transcripts are stored in your git repository** on the `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch. If your repository is public, this data is visible to anyone.\\n   283→\\n   284→Entire automatically redacts detected secrets (API keys, tokens, credentials) when writing to `entire/checkpoints/v1`, but redaction is best-effort. Temporary shadow branches used during a session may contain unredacted data and should not be pushed. See [docs/security-and-privacy.md](docs/security-and-privacy.md) for details.\\n   285→\\n   286→## Troubleshooting\\n   287→\\n   288→### Common Issues\\n   289→\\n   290→| Issue                    | Solution                                                                                  |\\n   291→|--------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n   292→| \\\"Not a git repository\\\"   | Navigate to a Git repository first                                                        |\\n   293→| \\\"Entire is disabled\\\"     | Run `entire enable`                                                                       |\\n   294→| \\\"No rewind points found\\\" | Work with Claude Code and commit (manual-commit) or wait for agent response (auto-commit) |\\n   295→| \\\"shadow branch conflict\\\" | Run `entire reset --force`                                                                |\\n   296→\\n   297→### SSH Authentication Errors\\n   298→\\n   299→If you see an error like this when running `entire resume`:\\n   300→\\n   301→```\\n   302→Failed to fetch metadata: failed to fetch entire/checkpoints/v1 from origin: ssh: handshake failed: ssh: unable to authenticate, attempted methods [none publickey], no supported methods remain\\n   303→```\\n   304→\\n   305→This is a [known issue with go-git's SSH handling](https://github.com/go-git/go-git/issues/411). Fix it by adding GitHub's host keys to your known_hosts file:\\n   306→\\n   307→```\\n   308→ssh-keyscan -t rsa github.com >> ~/.ssh/known_hosts\\n   309→ssh-keyscan -t ecdsa github.com >> ~/.ssh/known_hosts\\n   310→```\\n   311→\\n   312→### Debug Mode\\n   313→\\n   314→```\\n   315→# Via environment variable\\n   316→ENTIRE_LOG_LEVEL=debug entire status\\n   317→\\n   318→# Or via settings.local.json\\n   319→{\\n   320→  \\\"log_level\\\": \\\"debug\\\"\\n   321→}\\n   322→```\\n   323→\\n   324→### 