ge\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T13:16:43.547Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-5-20251101\",\"id\":\"msg_0136U8ok8zB9HxHsBE43CGwx\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_015wboNqo4pKFnKAtP4sWXDU\",\"name\":\"Write\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/opencode-agent/review-02.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 02\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-02-20\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: APPROVE\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nFrom review-01 (the original OpenCode implementation):\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: Path from agent hook - path validation - **ADDRESSED** (now uses `.entire/tmp/` within repo root instead of system temp)\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: Silent JSON parse errors may hide issues - **ADDRESSED** (now uses export JSON format which returns errors on invalid JSON instead of silently skipping invalid lines)\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: Idempotency check could use file hash - **STILL VALID** (not addressed in this refactor, but lower priority)\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: FileModificationTools should be exhaustive - **STILL VALID** (comment added documenting the dependency)\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nThis review covers the OpenCode refactor in the `soph/opencode-refactor` branch. The refactor changes OpenCode's transcript handling from:\\n- **Before**: Plugin writes JSONL transcript to temp file, passes path to hooks\\n- **After**: Plugin sends only session_id, Go handler calls `opencode export` to get native export JSON format\\n\\n### Commits Reviewed\\n- `cfd21966` - opencode refactor to use internal format and full logs\\n- `860b5a7b` - make sure we handle transcript position, add tmp file cleanup to cleanup command\\n\\n### Files Changed (17 files, +779/-488 lines)\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/cli_commands.go` - Added `runOpenCodeExport` function\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/entire_plugin.ts` - Simplified: removed transcript writing, now just sends session_id\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/lifecycle.go` - Now calls `opencode export` on turn-end\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/opencode.go` - ChunkTranscript/ReassembleTranscript updated for JSON format\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/transcript.go` - Migrated from JSONL to export JSON parsing\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/types.go` - Added export JSON types (ExportSession, ExportMessage, etc.)\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/clean.go` - Added temp file cleanup support\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_condensation.go` - Added OpenCode SliceFromMessage support\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/summarize/summarize.go` - Updated for export JSON format\\n- Test files updated accordingly\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\nNone.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n1. **[lifecycle.go:54] Suppressed error in path construction**\\n\\n   The error from `paths.RepoRoot()` is suppressed with `//nolint:errcheck`:\\n   ```go\\n   repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot() //nolint:errcheck // fallback to empty string is fine for path construction\\n   ```\\n\\n   While the comment explains the rationale, if `paths.RepoRoot()` fails in turn-start, the subsequent `fetchAndCacheExport` call (which also uses `paths.RepoRoot()`) will also fail but with a different error path. This is unlikely to cause issues in practice but creates two potential failure points.\\n\\n   **Suggestion**: Consider using a consistent approach - either handle the error in both places or document why the fallback to \\\".\\\" is acceptable:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   // Repo root may fail if called outside a repo (unlikely in hook context).\\n   // Fallback to \\\".\\\" is acceptable - the file will still be written, just\\n   // to current directory instead of .entire/tmp/.\\n   repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **[lifecycle.go:115-146] Test seam could be documented better**\\n\\n   The `fetchAndCacheExport` function has a test seam (checks if file already exists), which is documented in the function comment. However, the integration test helper (`SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd` in `hooks.go`) writes to `.entire/tmp/<session_id>.json`, but this isn't immediately obvious when reading the lifecycle code.\\n\\n   **Suggestion**: Add a cross-reference in the lifecycle.go comment pointing to the test helper that uses this seam.\\n\\n3. **[clean.go:106-121] deleteTempFiles could log which files failed to delete**\\n\\n   The `deleteTempFiles` function returns failed file names but doesn't include the error reason. When debugging cleanup issues, knowing *why* a file failed to delete (permission denied, file in use, etc.) would be helpful.\\n\\n   **Suggestion**: Consider changing to return errors with file names:\\n   ```go\\n   type tempFileDeleteError struct {\\n       File string\\n       Err  error\\n   }\\n   func deleteTempFiles(files []string) (deleted []string, failed []tempFileDeleteError)\\n   ```\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n1. **[entire_plugin.ts:14-15] In-memory stores still needed despite no transcript writing**\\n\\n   The `messageStore` and `partStore` are retained but their main use (reconstructing transcripts during shutdown) is no longer needed. They're now only used to detect new user messages for turn-start firing (line 66-68).\\n\\n   **Rationale for keeping**: The stores are still needed for the turn-start logic (detecting first text part of user message). Current approach is correct.\\n\\n2. **[opencode.go:79] Base size calculation is approximate**\\n\\n   ```go\\n   currentSize := len(`{\\\"info\\\":{},\\\"messages\\\":[]}`) // Base JSON structure size\\n   ```\\n\\n   This calculation doesn't account for the actual size of `session.Info` when marshaled. For accurate chunking, you'd need to marshal `session.Info` once and use its actual size. In practice, the session info is small, so this approximation is fine.\\n\\n3. **[transcript.go:47-71] SliceFromMessage returns nil on error**\\n\\n   Unlike other functions that return errors, `SliceFromMessage` returns `nil` on parse errors. This is consistent with `transcript.SliceFromLine` but could silently hide issues.\\n\\n   **Note**: This is an existing pattern, not a regression.\\n\\n4. **[clean.go:97-99] Only lists files, not subdirectories**\\n\\n   The `listTempFiles` function skips subdirectories (`if !entry.IsDir()`). This is correct for the current `.entire/tmp/` usage, but if subdirectories are ever added, they won't be cleaned up.\\n\\n5. **[manual_commit_condensation.go:202-208] Switch statement is more readable**\\n\\n   Good change from `if state.AgentType == agent.AgentTypeGemini` to a switch statement. Makes it clearer how different agents are handled.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n1. **Excellent architectural improvement** - Moving from plugin-written transcripts to `opencode export` has several benefits:\\n   - Eliminates race conditions between plugin shutdown and hook handler reading\\n   - Uses OpenCode's native export format, ensuring full transcript fidelity\\n   - Simplifies the plugin code significantly (152 lines removed)\\n   - Better testability (test seam in `fetchAndCacheExport`)\\n\\n2. **Clean type definitions** - The new `ExportSession`, `ExportMessage`, `MessageInfo` types in `types.go` clearly model the OpenCode export format with proper JSON tags and documentation.\\n\\n3. **Proper temp file cleanup** - Adding temp file cleanup to the `entire clean` command shows good attention to operational hygiene. The `.entire/tmp/` directory could accumulate stale files without this.\\n\\n4. **Test coverage maintained** - All tests updated to use the new export JSON format. The test helpers (`CreateOpenCodeTranscript`, `SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd`) were properly updated to write mock export data.\\n\\n5. **Transcript validation improved** - The `validateTranscriptJSONL` test helper now supports both JSON and JSONL formats, making it work correctly with OpenCode's JSON format.\\n\\n6. **Good error handling in export** - The `runOpenCodeExport` function properly handles:\\n   - Timeout with descriptive error\\n   - Exit errors with stderr context\\n   - Generic errors with wrapping\\n\\n7. **Backward compatible** - The change maintains the same external behavior (hooks, rewind, resume) while improving the internal implementation.\\n\\n## End-to-End Verification\\n\\nTraced the key paths through the refactored code:\\n\\n### Turn-End Checkpoint Flow\\n1. OpenCode plugin fires `session.idle` event\\n2. Plugin calls `entire hooks opencode turn-end` with `{session_id: \\\"...\\\"}` (no transcript path)\\n3. `lifecycle.go:ParseHookEvent` receives turn-end, calls `fetchAndCacheExport`\\n4. `fetchAndCacheExport` calls `runOpenCodeExport` which runs `opencode export <session_id>`\\n5. Export JSON is written to `.entire/tmp/<session_id>.json`\\n6. `agent.Event` returned with `SessionRef` pointing to the temp file\\n7. Lifecycle handler in `lifecycle.go` reads transcript from this path\\n8. Checkpoint is created with full export JSON data\\n\\n### Temp File Cleanup Flow\\n1. User runs `entire clean`\\n2. `listTempFiles()` reads `.entire/tmp/` directory\\n3. Files are listed in preview mode, or deleted in `--force` mode\\n4. Cleanup counts are reported\\n\\n### Integration Tests\\n- `TestOpenCodeSessionOperations` updated to use export JSON format\\n- `SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd` writes mock data to `.entire/tmp/` before calling hook\\n- Tests verify transcript parsing, modified file extraction, and round-trip\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n- **Overall assessment**: APPROVE\\n- **Key concerns**: Minor - error handling and logging improvements could be added\\n- **Estimated effort to address feedback**: ~30 minutes for documentation improvements\\n\\nThis refactor is a solid architectural improvement that:\\n1. Simplifies the OpenCode plugin by removing transcript writing responsibility\\n2. Uses OpenCode's native export format for better data fidelity\\n3. Improves 