il but with a different error path. This is unlikely to cause issues in practice but creates two potential failure points.\\n    54→\\n    55→   **Suggestion**: Consider using a consistent approach - either handle the error in both places or document why the fallback to \\\".\\\" is acceptable:\\n    56→\\n    57→   ```go\\n    58→   // Repo root may fail if called outside a repo (unlikely in hook context).\\n    59→   // Fallback to \\\".\\\" is acceptable - the file will still be written, just\\n    60→   // to current directory instead of .entire/tmp/.\\n    61→   repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\n    62→   ```\\n    63→\\n    64→2. **[lifecycle.go:115-146] Test seam could be documented better**\\n    65→\\n    66→   The `fetchAndCacheExport` function has a test seam (checks if file already exists), which is documented in the function comment. However, the integration test helper (`SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd` in `hooks.go`) writes to `.entire/tmp/<session_id>.json`, but this isn't immediately obvious when reading the lifecycle code.\\n    67→\\n    68→   **Suggestion**: Add a cross-reference in the lifecycle.go comment pointing to the test helper that uses this seam.\\n    69→\\n    70→3. **[clean.go:106-121] deleteTempFiles could log which files failed to delete**\\n    71→\\n    72→   The `deleteTempFiles` function returns failed file names but doesn't include the error reason. When debugging cleanup issues, knowing *why* a file failed to delete (permission denied, file in use, etc.) would be helpful.\\n    73→\\n    74→   **Suggestion**: Consider changing to return errors with file names:\\n    75→   ```go\\n    76→   type tempFileDeleteError struct {\\n    77→       File string\\n    78→       Err  error\\n    79→   }\\n    80→   func deleteTempFiles(files []string) (deleted []string, failed []tempFileDeleteError)\\n    81→   ```\\n    82→\\n    83→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n    84→\\n    85→1. **[entire_plugin.ts:14-15] In-memory stores still needed despite no transcript writing**\\n    86→\\n    87→   The `messageStore` and `partStore` are retained but their main use (reconstructing transcripts during shutdown) is no longer needed. They're now only used to detect new user messages for turn-start firing (line 66-68).\\n    88→\\n    89→   **Rationale for keeping**: The stores are still needed for the turn-start logic (detecting first text part of user message). Current approach is correct.\\n    90→\\n    91→2. **[opencode.go:79] Base size calculation is approximate**\\n    92→\\n    93→   ```go\\n    94→   currentSize := len(`{\\\"info\\\":{},\\\"messages\\\":[]}`) // Base JSON structure size\\n    95→   ```\\n    96→\\n    97→   This calculation doesn't account for the actual size of `session.Info` when marshaled. For accurate chunking, you'd need to marshal `session.Info` once and use its actual size. In practice, the session info is small, so this approximation is fine.\\n    98→\\n    99→3. **[transcript.go:47-71] SliceFromMessage returns nil on error**\\n   100→\\n   101→   Unlike other functions that return errors, `SliceFromMessage` returns `nil` on parse errors. This is consistent with `transcript.SliceFromLine` but could silently hide issues.\\n   102→\\n   103→   **Note**: This is an existing pattern, not a regression.\\n   104→\\n   105→4. **[clean.go:97-99] Only lists files, not subdirectories**\\n   106→\\n   107→   The `listTempFiles` function skips subdirectories (`if !entry.IsDir()`). This is correct for the current `.entire/tmp/` usage, but if subdirectories are ever added, they won't be cleaned up.\\n   108→\\n   109→5. **[manual_commit_condensation.go:202-208] Switch statement is more readable**\\n   110→\\n   111→   Good change from `if state.AgentType == agent.AgentTypeGemini` to a switch statement. Makes it clearer how different agents are handled.\\n   112→\\n   113→### Praise\\n   114→\\n   115→1. **Excellent architectural improvement** - Moving from plugin-written transcripts to `opencode export` has several benefits:\\n   116→   - Eliminates race conditions between plugin shutdown and hook handler reading\\n   117→   - Uses OpenCode's native export format, ensuring full transcript fidelity\\n   118→   - Simplifies the plugin code significantly (152 lines removed)\\n   119→   - Better testability (test seam in `fetchAndCacheExport`)\\n   120→\\n   121→2. **Clean type definitions** - The new `ExportSession`, `ExportMessage`, `MessageInfo` types in `types.go` clearly model the OpenCode export format with proper JSON tags and documentation.\\n   122→\\n   123→3. **Proper temp file cleanup** - Adding temp file cleanup to the `entire clean` command shows good attention to operational hygiene. The `.entire/tmp/` directory could accumulate stale files without this.\\n   124→\\n   125→4. **Test coverage maintained** - All tests updated to use the new export JSON format. The test helpers (`CreateOpenCodeTranscript`, `SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd`) were properly updated to write mock export data.\\n   126→\\n   127→5. **Transcript validation improved** - The `validateTranscriptJSONL` test helper now supports both JSON and JSONL formats, making it work correctly with OpenCode's JSON format.\\n   128→\\n   129→6. **Good error handling in export** - The `runOpenCodeExport` function properly handles:\\n   130→   - Timeout with descriptive error\\n   131→   - Exit errors with stderr context\\n   132→   - Generic errors with wrapping\\n   133→\\n   134→7. **Backward compatible** - The change maintains the same external behavior (hooks, rewind, resume) while improving the internal implementation.\\n   135→\\n   136→## End-to-End Verification\\n   137→\\n   138→Traced the key paths through the refactored code:\\n   139→\\n   140→### Turn-End Checkpoint Flow\\n   141→1. OpenCode plugin fires `session.idle` event\\n   142→2. Plugin calls `entire hooks opencode turn-end` with `{session_id: \\\"...\\\"}` (no transcript path)\\n   143→3. `lifecycle.go:ParseHookEvent` receives turn-end, calls `fetchAndCacheExport`\\n   144→4. `fetchAndCacheExport` calls `runOpenCodeExport` which runs `opencode export <session_id>`\\n   145→5. Export JSON is written to `.entire/tmp/<session_id>.json`\\n   146→6. `agent.Event` returned with `SessionRef` pointing to the temp file\\n   147→7. Lifecycle handler in `lifecycle.go` reads transcript from this path\\n   148→8. Checkpoint is created with full export JSON data\\n   149→\\n   150→### Temp File Cleanup Flow\\n   151→1. User runs `entire clean`\\n   152→2. `listTempFiles()` reads `.entire/tmp/` directory\\n   153→3. Files are listed in preview mode, or deleted in `--force` mode\\n   154→4. Cleanup counts are reported\\n   155→\\n   156→### Integration Tests\\n   157→- `TestOpenCodeSessionOperations` updated to use export JSON format\\n   158→- `SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd` writes mock data to `.entire/tmp/` before calling hook\\n   159→- Tests verify transcript parsing, modified file extraction, and round-trip\\n   160→\\n   161→## Summary\\n   162→\\n   163→- **Overall assessment**: APPROVE\\n   164→- **Key concerns**: Minor - error handling and logging improvements could be added\\n   165→- **Estimated effort to address feedback**: ~30 minutes for documentation improvements\\n   166→\\n   167→This refactor is a solid architectural improvement that:\\n   168→1. Simplifies the OpenCode plugin by removing transcript writing responsibility\\n   169→2. Uses OpenCode's native export format for better data fidelity\\n   170→3. Improves testability with clear test seams\\n   171→4. Adds proper temp file cleanup to prevent accumulation\\n   172→\\n   173→The code is well-tested (all CI tests pass, lint clean), maintains backward compatibility, and follows established patterns in the codebase. Ready for merge.\\n   174→\\n\\n<system-reminder>\\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\\n</system-reminder>\\n\"}]},\"uuid\":\"1043f846-683b-43fc-b6cd-d1ac71832049\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T13:19:52.468Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/opencode-agent/review-02.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 02\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-02-20\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: APPROVE\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nFrom review-01 (the original OpenCode implementation):\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: Path from agent hook - path validation - **ADDRESSED** (now uses `.entire/tmp/` within repo root instead of system temp)\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: Silent JSON parse errors may hide issues - **ADDRESSED** (now uses export JSON format which returns errors on invalid JSON instead of silently skipping invalid lines)\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: Idempotency check could use file hash - **STILL VALID** (not addressed in this refactor, but lower priority)\\n- [x] Issue from review-01: FileModificationTools should be exhaustive - **STILL VALID** (comment added documenting the dependency)\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nThis review covers the OpenCode refactor in the `soph/opencode-refactor` branch. The refactor changes OpenCode's transcript handling from:\\n- **Before**: Plugin writes JSONL transcript to temp file, passes path to hooks\\n- **After**: Plugin sends only session_id, Go handler calls `opencode export` to get native export JSON format\\n\\n### Commits Reviewed\\n- `cfd21966` - opencode refactor to use internal format and full logs\\n- `860b5a7b` - make sure we handle transcript position, add tmp file cleanup to cleanup command\\n\\n### Files Changed (17 files, +779/-488 lines)\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/cli_commands.go` - Added `runOpenCodeExport` function\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/entire_plugin.ts` - Simplified: removed transcript writing, now just sends session_id\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/lifecycle.go` - Now calls `opencode export` on turn-end\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/opencode.go` - ChunkTranscript/ReassembleTranscript updated for JSON format\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/transcript.go` - Migrated from JSONL to export JSON parsing\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/types.go` - Added export JSON types (ExportSession, ExportMessage, etc.)\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/clean.go` - Added temp file cleanup support\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_condensation.go` - Added OpenCode SliceFromMessage support\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/summarize/summarize.go` - Updated for export JSON format\\n- Test files updated accordingly\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\nNone.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n1. **[lifecycle.go:54] Suppressed error in path construction**\\n\\n   The error from `paths.RepoRoot()` is suppressed with `//nolint:errcheck`:\\n   ```go\\n   repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot() //nolint:errcheck // fallback to empty string is fine for path construction\\n   ```\\n\\n   While the comment explains the rationale, if `paths.RepoRoot()` fails in turn-start, the subsequent `fetchAndCacheExport` call (which also uses `paths.RepoRoot()`) will also fail but with a different error path. This is unlikely to cause issues in practice but creates two potential failure points.\\n\\n   **Suggestion**: Consider using a consistent approach - either handle the error in both places or document why the fallback to \\\".\\\" is acceptable:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   // Repo root may fail if called outside a repo (unlikely in hook context).\\n   // Fallback to \\\".\\\" is acceptable - the file will still be written, just\\n   // to current directory instead of .entire/tmp/.\\n   repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **[lifecycle.go:115-146] Test seam could be documented better**\\n\\n   The `fetchAndCacheExport` function has a test seam (checks if file already exists), which is documented in the function comment. However, the integration test helper (`SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd` in `hooks.go`) writes to `.entire/tmp/<session_id>.json`, but this isn't immediately obvious when reading the lifecycle code.\\n\\n   **Suggestion**: Add a cross-reference in the lifecycle.go comment pointing to the test helper that uses this seam.\\n\\n3. **[clean.go:106-121] deleteTempFiles could log which files failed to delete**\\n\\n   The `deleteTempFiles` function returns failed file names but doesn't include the error reason. When debugging cleanup issues, knowing *why* a file failed to delete (permission denied, file in use, etc.) would be helpful.\\n\\n   **Suggestion**: Consider changing to return errors with file names:\\n   ```go\\n   type tempFileDeleteError struct {\\n       File string\\n       Err  error\\n   }\\n   func deleteTempFiles(files []string) (deleted []string, failed []tempFileDeleteError)\\n   ```\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n1. **[entire_plugin.ts:14-15] In-memory stores still needed despite no transcript writing**\\n\\n   The `messageStore` and `partStore` are retained but their main use (reconstructing transcripts during shutdown) is no longer needed. They're now only used to detect new user messages for turn-start firing (line 66-68).\\n\\n   **Rationale for keeping**: The stores are still needed for the turn-start logic (detecting first text part of user message). Current approach is correct.\\n\\n2. **[opencode.go:79] Base size calculation is approximate**\\n\\n   ```go\\n   currentSize := len(`{\\\"info\\\":{},\\\"messages\\\":[]}`) // Base JSON structure size\\n   ```\\n\\n   This calculation doesn't account for the actual size of `session.Info` when marshaled. For accurate chunking, you'd need to marshal `session.Info` once and use its actual size. In practice, the session info is small, so this approximation is fine.\\n\\n3. **[transcript.go:47-71] SliceFromMessage returns nil on error**\\n\\n   Unlike other functions that return errors, `SliceFromMessage` returns `nil` on parse errors. This is consistent with `transcript.SliceFromLine` but could silently hide issues.\\n\\n   **Note**: This is an existing pattern, not a regression.\\n\\n4. **[clean.go:97-99] Only lists files, not subdirectories**\\n\\n   The `listTempFiles` function skips subdirectories (`if !entry.IsDir()`). This is correct for the current `.entire/tmp/` usage, but if subdirectories are ever added, they won't be cleaned up.\\n\\n5. **[manual_commit_condensation.go:202-208] Switch statement is more readable**\\n\\n   Good change from `if state.AgentType == agent.AgentTypeGemini` to a switch statement. Makes it clearer how different agents are handled.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n1. **Excellent architectural improvement** - Moving from plugin-written transcripts to `opencode export` has several benefits:\\n   - Eliminates race conditions between plugin shutdown and hook handler reading\\n   - Uses OpenCode's native export format, ensuring full transcript fidelity\\n   - Simplifies the plugin code significantly (152 lines removed)\\n   - Better testability (test seam in `fetchAndCacheExport`)\\n\\n2. **Clean type definitions** - The new `ExportSession`, `ExportMessage`, `MessageInfo` types in `types.go` clearly model the OpenCode export format with proper JSON tags and documentation.\\n\\n3. **Proper temp file cleanup** - Adding temp file cleanup to the `entire clean` command shows good attention to operational hygiene. The `.entire/tmp/` directory could accumulate stale files without this.\\n\\n4. **Test coverage maintained** - All tests updated to use the new export JSON format. The test helpers (`CreateOpenCodeTranscript`, `SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd`) were properly updated to write mock export data.\\n\\n5. **Transcript validation improved** - The `validateTranscriptJSONL` test helper now supports both JSON and JSONL formats, making it work correctly with OpenCode's JSON format.\\n\\n6. **Good error handling in export** - The `runOpenCodeExport` function properly handles:\\n   - Timeout with descriptive error\\n   - Exit errors with stderr context\\n   - Generic errors with wrapping\\n\\n7. **Backward compatible** - The change maintains the same external behavior (hooks, rewind, resume) while improving the internal implementation.\\n\\n## End-to-End Verification\\n\\nTraced the key paths through the refactored code:\\n\\n### Turn-End Checkpoint Flow\\n1. OpenCode plugin fires `session.idle` event\\n2. Plugin calls `entire hooks opencode turn-end` with `{session_id: \\\"...\\\"}` (no transcript path)\\n3. `lifecycle.go:ParseHookEvent` receives turn-end, calls `fetchAndCacheExport`\\n4. `fetchAndCacheExport` calls `runOpenCodeExport` which runs `opencode export <session_id>`\\n5. Export JSON is written to `.entire/tmp/<session_id>.json`\\n6. `agent.Event` returned with `SessionRef` pointing to the temp file\\n7. Lifecycle handler in `lifecycle.go` reads transcript from this path\\n8. Checkpoint is created with full export JSON data\\n\\n### Temp File Cleanup Flow\\n1. User runs `entire clean`\\n2. `listTempFiles()` reads `.entire/tmp/` directory\\n3. Files are listed in preview mode, or deleted in `--force` mode\\n4. Cleanup counts are reported\\n\\n### Integration Tests\\n- `TestOpenCodeSessionOperations` updated to use export JSON format\\n- `SimulateOpenCodeTurnEnd` writes mock data to `.entire/tmp/` before calling hook\\n- Tests verify transcript parsing, modified file extraction, and round-trip\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n- **Overall assessment**: APPROVE\\n- **Key concerns**: Minor - error handling and logging improvements could be added\\n- **Estimated effort to address feedback**: ~30 minutes for documentation improvements\\n\\nThis refactor is a solid architectural improvement that:\\n1. Simplifies the OpenCode plugin by removing transcript writing responsibility\\n2. Uses OpenCode's native export format for better data fidelity\\n3. Improves testability with clear test seams\\n4. Adds proper temp file cleanup to prevent accumulation\\n\\nThe code is well-tested (all CI tests pass, lint clean), maintains backward compatibility, and follows established patterns in the codebase. Ready for merge.\\n\",\"numLines\":174,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":174}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"cc08cdbc-df06-4709-b5bf-87dceb0f6069\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"1043f846-683b-43fc-b6cd-d1ac71832049\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"5fa62c96-990b-404b-ba97-2d130d82ab6e\",\"version\":\"2.1.17\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-refactor\",\"slug\":\"eager-tickling-nova\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-5-20251101\",\"id\":\"msg_01EgPbdiRU7WHm72NxXmMKBy\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user wants to see the details of the 3 \\\"Important\\\" issues. Let me extract those from the review file I just read.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":8,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":3258,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":29810,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":3258},\"output_tokens\":2,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYKPVforsneGvxg57MUc6\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"9dde27ab-3b42-43de-920a-8cabc7aefb5b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T13:19:55.177Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9dde27ab-3b42-43de-920a-8cabc7aefb5b\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"5fa62c96-990b-404b-ba97-2d130d82ab6e\",\"version\":\"2.1.17\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/opencode-refactor\",\"slug\":\"eager-tickling-nova\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-5-20251101\",\"id\":\"msg_01EgPbdiRU7WHm72NxXmMKBy\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here are the 3 \\\"Important (Sho